    "narrative": "The Zurich Zebras enter today\u2019s slate with **Pete Crow-Armstrong** serving as our clear offensive anchor; his score of 82.13 is a standout, driven by a favorable matchup against the high xERA of Roki Sasaki. While his spot at the bottom of the order typically drags down his production, his dynamic platoon advantage (+14%) and the favorable wind conditions at the venue provide the perfect storm for a multi-steal or extra-base hit performance. Close behind, **Junior Caminero** (73.53) and **Trea Turner** (68.86) offer high-floor utility. **Trea Turner** remains our primary catalyst for stolen bases at the top of the lineup, and despite facing a competent arm in Bryce Elder, his elite order position makes him a high-efficiency play. Similarly, **Kyle Schwarber** continues to be a core piece of our daily construction, leveraging an impressive 0.402 xwOBA to maintain a 65.76 score even against a solid matchup.\n\nOur bench decisions today were heavily influenced by the strict Zebras 40.0 efficiency floor, which saw both **Jerar Encarnacion** (39.52) and **Victor Scott II** (39.50) narrowly excluded. While **Victor Scott II** provides the speed profile we covet, the combination of a difficult matchup against George Kirby and a bottom-of-the-order assignment suppressed his output below our threshold. The lineup construction also keeps a close eye on volatility: **Dillon Dingler** (43.97) and **Josh Smith** (44.87) represent our most marginal starts. **Dillon Dingler** specifically suffers from a significant -15% dynamic platoon hit against Brady Singer, which necessitates careful monitoring as official lineups drop. We remain cautious regarding the \"Lineup Pending\" status for all starters, as any shifts for players like **Gary Sanchez** or **Hyeseong Kim** could necessitate mid-day adjustments to ensure we aren't burning limited game caps on suboptimal slots.",
